Sol. but who
ſhall be judge, whether they be publique and neceſſary? The major part in either of the Houſes, for paſſing of Bills ſo pretended, may be but one or two voyces, or very few, and perhaps of no judicious men; is it not then fitter or more agreeable to reaſon, that his Majeſty and Councell of State, his twelve Judges, his Sergeants, Attorney, and Solicitor, twelve Maſters of the Chancery, ſhould judge of the conveniency and benefit of ſuch Bills for the publick good, rather then a minor, (of which ſort there may be in the Houſes) or a weake man, or a few, who oftentimes carry it by making the major part, which involves the conſent of all? Let reaſon determine.

